00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Hello, this is 6-minute English from BBCLearningEnglish. I'm Georgie.

4
00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:20.000
And I'm Neil. In this program, we're talking about the immune system, which is the body's natural defense against getting ill.

5
00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:25.000
Now, Georgie, is there anything you do to boost your immune system?

6
00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:30.000
Yes, I try to eat lots of oranges, which apparently have lots of vitamin C.

7
00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:35.000
And there are lots of things people do to try to improve their immune system and say healthier.

8
00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:41.000
Like eating certain foods, taking vitamins, or even activities like swimming in cold water.

9
00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:45.000
We'll find out how useful some of these techniques are in today's program.

10
00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:47.000
But first, Georgie, a question.

11
00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:49.000
We all know the common cold.

12
00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:53.000
Now, that's the illness that makes you cough and sneeze have a sore throat and headache.

13
00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:58.000
But how many colds does the average adult get in the UK each year?

14
00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:03.000
Is it a 2-3, b, 4-5, or c7-8?

15
00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:04.000
Hmm.

16
00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:08.000
8 would be a lot. I'm going to go with a 2-3 colds a year.

17
00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:12.000
Well, we'll find out at the end of the program if you're right.

18
00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:19.000
Now, many people can become ill over the winter with diseases like colds, flu, and COVID-19.

19
00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:23.000
Host of BBC Radio 4 program inside health, James Gallagher,

20
00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:27.000
gathered some experts to talk about immune systems.

21
00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:32.000
And he started off by asking whether they'd had more illnesses than usual this winter.

22
00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:34.000
Hello? Hi.

23
00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:37.000
Right. How has everyone been this winter?

24
00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:42.000
Because I've had a rotten one, and I have felt constantly ill since about November.

25
00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:43.000
John?

26
00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:46.000
I have not had anything yet, touch with.

27
00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:49.000
Okay. Let's see what I can infect you with by the end of the show, Margaret.

28
00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:52.000
I was pretty unwilling to September. I had what presumed to be covered,

29
00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:56.000
but I've been all right since my old snuffles are saved.

30
00:01:56.000 --> 00:01:58.000
Elena, I really need someone to back me up.

31
00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:01.000
At no, sorry. I've been absolutely 100% tickety blue.

32
00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:05.000
Unlike James, Professor John Tragoaning hasn't been ill.

33
00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:11.000
John uses the expression Touchwood, which is an informal phrase, said in order to avoid bad luck.

34
00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:17.000
Dr. Margaret McCartney was unwell in September, but has only had a few snuffles since.

35
00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:22.000
Snuffles is an informal word used to describe minor illnesses that affect your nose.

36
00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:24.000
We can also say Sniffles.

37
00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:31.000
Host James is surprised that nobody has been ill and says to Professor Elena Riley back me up.

38
00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:36.000
If you ask someone to back you up, you're asking for them to say something which supports your opinion.

39
00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:39.000
But Elena has had a healthy winter too.

40
00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:45.000
She's been tickety blue, which is an informal phrase meaning everything's fine or in good order.

41
00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:53.000
Throughout the winter, many people try different techniques, like taking supplements or eating certain foods to boost their immune system,

42
00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:57.000
to improve their body's natural defenses against disease.

43
00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:05.000
Host of BBC Radio Fores Inside Health, James Gallagher, asks Dr. Margaret McCartney whether some of these products are successful.

44
00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:09.000
Okay, quick-fire round Margaret, Echinacea.

45
00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:10.000
No.

46
00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:11.000
Turmeric.

47
00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:12.000
No.

48
00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:13.000
Ginger shots.

49
00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:14.000
No.

50
00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:16.000
This is a very, very good quiz.

51
00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:20.000
What about the stuff you squirt at you nose when you're at the beginning of an infection?

52
00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:25.000
Interesting, but not any better than normal ceilings, free, just saltwater.

53
00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:33.000
In fact, according to Margaret, there isn't enough evidence that many popular health products can actually change the way your immune system works.

54
00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:37.000
Another popular health trend in the UK is cold water swimming.

55
00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:46.000
People who swim in cold water say it's good for their mental health, and they also believe it makes them less likely to get ill during the winter months.

56
00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:56.000
But scientists aren't sure about the benefits of cold water swimming for the immune system yet, as Professor John Tragoaning explains to BBC Radio Fores Inside Health.

57
00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:00.000
The social element actually is really important. It probably is beneficial to do.

58
00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:13.000
You reduce stress and cortisol dampens your immune system. So actually if you're stressed, then maybe you are more prone to infection, and that may be why that benefit of being with people, nice people that you like in nice places is helping.

59
00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:16.000
But I don't think it's unique to cold water swimming.

60
00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:20.000
I think you can probably get it from dancing or singing or going for a run.

61
00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:26.000
John says that cortisol, a chemical associated with stress, dampens the immune system.

62
00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:29.000
Here, dampens means makes weaker.

63
00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:36.000
We also have a common expression dampens someone's spirits, which means to make them less enthusiastic about something.

64
00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:41.000
John says that there is evidence that people who are stressed are more prone to infection.

65
00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:45.000
If you're more prone to something, it's more likely to happen to you.

66
00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:57.000
It could be that cold water swimming reduces stress, and so it helps people's immune systems work well, but there are lots of other activities that could have the same effect, and help people have fewer colds over winter.

67
00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:03.000
It reminds me of my question, Georgie. I asked how many colds the average UK adult has a year.

68
00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:05.000
And I said 2-3.

69
00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:08.000
And that is the correct answer, so well done.

70
00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:09.000
Thank you.

71
00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:17.000
Okay, let's recap the vocabulary we've learned starting with Touch Word, which is an expression used often in speech to avoid bad luck.

72
00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:22.000
Snuffles or sniffles are minor illnesses that affect your nose.

73
00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:27.000
If you ask someone to back you up, you want them to say something to support your opinion.

74
00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:31.000
The expression tickety-boo means fine and in good order.

75
00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:33.000
If you dampen something, you make it weaker.

76
00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:38.000
And the expression dampens someone's spirits means you make them less enthusiastic about something.

77
00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:43.000
And if you're more prone to something, it's more likely to happen to you.

